HERO_STORIES = {'dajane-gurmessa': {'story': 'Dajane Gurmessa was born in 1941 in the highlands of Bale, in a village where the morning fog never quite left the acacia trees until noon. He was the fourth son of a farmer and a weaver, and grew up listening to the oral histories his grandmother recited each evening by the fire.\n\nHe walked twelve kilometers each morning to attend school in the nearest town, carrying his books wrapped in cloth against the rain. He finished first in his class every year. When he was nineteen, he was selected for teacher training in Addis Ababa, and when he returned three years later, he refused offers to teach in the city. He came back to Bale. He came back to his people.\n\nFor thirty-eight years, Dajane taught primary school in the same dusty classroom where he had first learned to read. He taught over 2,000 children. He taught their parents, in adult literacy classes he ran every Saturday morning. He taught in Afaan Oromoo at a time when it was not officially permitted, hiding his lesson materials under the floorboards when inspectors came from the regional capital. He believed — and he said this openly, without apology — that a child who cannot learn in their mother tongue is being asked to think in a foreign land.\n\nBeyond the classroom, he served as an informal mediator in land disputes, property disagreements, and family conflicts. Communities across three neighboring villages sought his counsel. His method was patience: he would listen to every side completely before speaking. He never raised his voice.\n\nIn his final years, he worked with younger community members to record and transcribe the oral histories he had carried in memory since childhood — proverbs, poems, ceremonial songs, birth and death rites. He filled eleven handwritten notebooks, which his family now preserves.\n\nDajane Gurmessa died in February 2019, at the age of seventy-seven, surrounded by his children and grandchildren. At his funeral, the mourners included former students now in their fifties and sixties, who had traveled from as far as Dire Dawa and Nairobi to pay their respects. One of them, now a university professor, said simply: He is the reason I can read.\n\nHe is survived by his wife Chaltu, four children, and eleven grandchildren. His notebooks are being digitized by volunteers in Robe. He asked, in his final months, that the proverb inscribed above his classroom door be remembered: Namni beekumsa hin qabne muka biqiltuu miti — A person without knowledge is not even a sapling.', 'story_en': 'Dajane Gurmessa was born in 1941 in the highlands of Bale, in a village where the morning fog never quite left the acacia trees until noon. He was the fourth son of a farmer and a weaver, and grew up listening to the oral histories his grandmother recited each evening by the fire.\n\nHe walked twelve kilometers each morning to attend school in the nearest town, carrying his books wrapped in cloth against the rain. He finished first in his class every year. When he was nineteen, he was selected for teacher training in Addis Ababa, and when he returned three years later, he refused offers to teach in the city. He came back to Bale. He came back to his people.\n\nFor thirty-eight years, Dajane taught primary school in the same dusty classroom where he had first learned to read. He taught over 2,000 children. He taught their parents, in adult literacy classes he ran every Saturday morning. He taught in Afaan Oromoo at a time when it was not officially permitted, hiding his lesson materials under the floorboards when inspectors came from the regional capital. He believed — and he said this openly, without apology — that a child who cannot learn in their mother tongue is being asked to think in a foreign land.\n\nBeyond the classroom, he served as an informal mediator in land disputes, property disagreements, and family conflicts. Communities across three neighboring villages sought his counsel. His method was patience: he would listen to every side completely before speaking. He never raised his voice.\n\nIn his final years, he worked with younger community members to record and transcribe the oral histories he had carried in memory since childhood — proverbs, poems, ceremonial songs, birth and death rites. He filled eleven handwritten notebooks, which his family now preserves.\n\nDajane Gurmessa died in February 2019, at the age of seventy-seven, surrounded by his children and grandchildren. At his funeral, the mourners included former students now in their fifties and sixties, who had traveled from as far as Dire Dawa and Nairobi to pay their respects. One of them, now a university professor, said simply: He is the reason I can read.\n\nHe is survived by his wife Chaltu, four children, and eleven grandchildren. His notebooks are being digitized by volunteers in Robe. He asked, in his final months, that the proverb inscribed above his classroom door be remembered: Namni beekumsa hin qabne muka biqiltuu miti — A person without knowledge is not even a sapling.', 'story_om': ''}, 'sinbirroo-halake': {'story': 'Sinbirroo Halake was named after the bird whose song is said to arrive before the rain — a name that suited her perfectly. Born in 1972 in Assela to a mother who had never attended school and a father who insisted she attend every day, she grew up understanding that education was not a given but a gift that could be taken away. That understanding made her fierce.\n\nShe qualified as a primary school teacher in 1993 and was assigned to a school in a rural sub-district where most of the students were boys. The pattern was familiar: at harvest time, girls were the first to be kept home to help with the fields. At the end of the year, half the girls who had enrolled in September were gone. Sinbirroo refused to accept this as normal.\n\nShe began visiting families on weekends, not to lecture but to listen. She learned what the barriers actually were — in some households, the school was too far and the road felt unsafe; in others, families believed education was wasted on a daughter who would marry. She adapted her response to each case. For the distance problem, she organised a walking group of older students who would escort younger girls. For the marriage question, she invited successful women from the regional town to speak at community gatherings. She framed girls\' education not as an outside imposition but as something Oromo communities had always valued — the ability of every person to contribute fully to the life of the community.\n\nWithin four years, female enrolment at her school had risen from thirty-one percent to sixty-eight percent. Officials from the regional education bureau came to study what she had done. She gave them tea and told them honestly that none of it required extra funding — only a willingness to see the problem clearly and keep showing up.\n\nIn 2008, Sinbirroo co-founded a small school specifically for girls who had already dropped out — those deemed too old for standard enrolment or too far behind to be welcomed back. She called it Guddina, meaning growth. By the time of her death in 2023 at the age of fifty-one, the school had graduated over four hundred young women, many of whom had continued into secondary and higher education.\n\nShe died unexpectedly of a heart condition that she had quietly managed for years without telling her colleagues, unwilling, those who knew her said, to give anyone a reason to worry about her carrying the work. At her memorial, one of her students read from an essay Sinbirroo had written in 1995: "The girl who is taught to read will teach her children to read, and they will teach theirs. The seed does not know how far it will travel."', 'story_en': 'Sinbirroo Halake was named after the bird whose song is said to arrive before the rain — a name that suited her perfectly. Born in 1972 in Assela to a mother who had never attended school and a father who insisted she attend every day, she grew up understanding that education was not a given but a gift that could be taken away. That understanding made her fierce.\n\nShe qualified as a primary school teacher in 1993 and was assigned to a school in a rural sub-district where most of the students were boys. The pattern was familiar: at harvest time, girls were the first to be kept home to help with the fields. At the end of the year, half the girls who had enrolled in September were gone. Sinbirroo refused to accept this as normal.\n\nShe began visiting families on weekends, not to lecture but to listen. She learned what the barriers actually were — in some households, the school was too far and the road felt unsafe; in others, families believed education was wasted on a daughter who would marry. She adapted her response to each case. For the distance problem, she organised a walking group of older students who would escort younger girls. For the marriage question, she invited successful women from the regional town to speak at community gatherings. She framed girls\' education not as an outside imposition but as something Oromo communities had always valued — the ability of every person to contribute fully to the life of the community.\n\nWithin four years, female enrolment at her school had risen from thirty-one percent to sixty-eight percent. Officials from the regional education bureau came to study what she had done. She gave them tea and told them honestly that none of it required extra funding — only a willingness to see the problem clearly and keep showing up.\n\nIn 2008, Sinbirroo co-founded a small school specifically for girls who had already dropped out — those deemed too old for standard enrolment or too far behind to be welcomed back. She called it Guddina, meaning growth. By the time of her death in 2023 at the age of fifty-one, the school had graduated over four hundred young women, many of whom had continued into secondary and higher education.\n\nShe died unexpectedly of a heart condition that she had quietly managed for years without telling her colleagues, unwilling, those who knew her said, to give anyone a reason to worry about her carrying the work. At her memorial, one of her students read from an essay Sinbirroo had written in 1995: "The girl who is taught to read will teach her children to read, and they will teach theirs. The seed does not know how far it will travel."', 'story_om': ''}, 'dedo-roba': {'story': 'Dedo Roba was the first trained nurse from the village of Jarra — a fact that almost did not happen. Her father, a progressive man by the standards of his time, argued for three days with village elders who felt a girl\'s place was in the home and not in a clinic. He won, barely, and Dedo left for Robe at sixteen to begin her training. She returned five years later with a certificate, a small medical kit, and the unshakeable belief that illness was not fate.\n\nThe government clinic assigned to Jarra was understaffed and often without supplies. For the first decade of her career, Dedo improvised — sterilising equipment with alcohol she distilled herself when antiseptic ran out, tracking down vaccines through a personal network of health workers across the zone, driving to supply depots in a borrowed truck when the official delivery chain failed. She became expert at making the system work for her community when the system itself showed no interest in doing so.\n\nHer most lasting achievement was a vaccination campaign she organised in 1991 across fourteen villages, covering children for measles, tuberculosis, and tetanus. The campaign had no official budget. Dedo coordinated it entirely through personal relationships — convincing local leaders to allow community gatherings, persuading mothers who were sceptical of injections, training two young women in each village to assist with record-keeping. In the three years following the campaign, child mortality in the area dropped by nearly a third.\n\nShe also trained fourteen community health workers during her career, each of whom went on to serve their own villages. She called this her "multiplier" — the understanding that one nurse could not reach everyone, but could train people who would. Several of those she trained have since become registered nurses themselves.\n\nDedo Roba died in 2020 at the age of sixty, still working. She had not taken a full week off in thirty years. Her colleagues at the clinic held a quiet ceremony the morning after she passed. On the wall of the waiting room, they hung a hand-lettered sign that read, in Afaan Oromoo: "She came when you called, day or night. She did not wait to be asked."', 'story_en': 'Dedo Roba was the first trained nurse from the village of Jarra — a fact that almost did not happen. Her father, a progressive man by the standards of his time, argued for three days with village elders who felt a girl\'s place was in the home and not in a clinic. He won, barely, and Dedo left for Robe at sixteen to begin her training. She returned five years later with a certificate, a small medical kit, and the unshakeable belief that illness was not fate.\n\nThe government clinic assigned to Jarra was understaffed and often without supplies. For the first decade of her career, Dedo improvised — sterilising equipment with alcohol she distilled herself when antiseptic ran out, tracking down vaccines through a personal network of health workers across the zone, driving to supply depots in a borrowed truck when the official delivery chain failed. She became expert at making the system work for her community when the system itself showed no interest in doing so.\n\nHer most lasting achievement was a vaccination campaign she organised in 1991 across fourteen villages, covering children for measles, tuberculosis, and tetanus. The campaign had no official budget. Dedo coordinated it entirely through personal relationships — convincing local leaders to allow community gatherings, persuading mothers who were sceptical of injections, training two young women in each village to assist with record-keeping. In the three years following the campaign, child mortality in the area dropped by nearly a third.\n\nShe also trained fourteen community health workers during her career, each of whom went on to serve their own villages. She called this her "multiplier" — the understanding that one nurse could not reach everyone, but could train people who would. Several of those she trained have since become registered nurses themselves.\n\nDedo Roba died in 2020 at the age of sixty, still working. She had not taken a full week off in thirty years. Her colleagues at the clinic held a quiet ceremony the morning after she passed. On the wall of the waiting room, they hung a hand-lettered sign that read, in Afaan Oromoo: "She came when you called, day or night. She did not wait to be asked."', 'story_om': ''}, 'wako-guutuu': {'story': 'Wako Guutuu was born in 1935 in Dello Mena, in the deep forests of the Bale mountains, at a time when the Gadaa system — the ancient Oromo system of democratic governance — was still lived and practised, not merely remembered. He came from a family of Abbaa Gadaa, hereditary custodians of the system\'s laws and ceremonies, and from childhood he was trained to memorise what could not be written: the genealogies of clans, the boundaries of customary territories, the terms of ancient peace agreements between communities.\n\nBy the time he was forty, Wako had become the most trusted oral historian in three districts. People came to him not only to hear history but to resolve disputes. He could recite from memory the terms of agreements made between communities two generations before his birth, and he used this knowledge to mediate conflicts over land, water, and grazing rights that might otherwise have turned violent. Local government officials, many of whom initially viewed him with suspicion, eventually began inviting him to participate in administrative proceedings because no written document could match what he carried in his mind.\n\nIn 1989, a researcher from Addis Ababa University spent three months with Wako recording his oral accounts. The resulting archive — over sixty hours of recordings — is now held at the university\'s Institute of Ethiopian Studies and remains one of the most comprehensive records of Bale Oromo customary law and history in existence. Wako insisted on one condition: everything must be recorded in Afaan Oromoo first, with translation secondary. "The meaning lives inside the language," he said. "When you take it out, something is always left behind."\n\nHe participated in Gadaa ceremonies into his seventies, walking long distances to be present even when his health was poor. He refused to allow the ceremonies to be abbreviated or modernised for convenience. He believed that partial preservation was a kind of forgetting dressed in the clothes of memory.\n\nWako Guutuu died peacefully in 2018 at the age of eighty-three. At the ceremony marking his death, his eldest son recited a genealogy stretching back seventeen generations — knowledge that Wako himself had passed to him. Those who heard it said the names sounded like water returning to its source.', 'story_en': 'Wako Guutuu was born in 1935 in Dello Mena, in the deep forests of the Bale mountains, at a time when the Gadaa system — the ancient Oromo system of democratic governance — was still lived and practised, not merely remembered. He came from a family of Abbaa Gadaa, hereditary custodians of the system\'s laws and ceremonies, and from childhood he was trained to memorise what could not be written: the genealogies of clans, the boundaries of customary territories, the terms of ancient peace agreements between communities.\n\nBy the time he was forty, Wako had become the most trusted oral historian in three districts. People came to him not only to hear history but to resolve disputes. He could recite from memory the terms of agreements made between communities two generations before his birth, and he used this knowledge to mediate conflicts over land, water, and grazing rights that might otherwise have turned violent. Local government officials, many of whom initially viewed him with suspicion, eventually began inviting him to participate in administrative proceedings because no written document could match what he carried in his mind.\n\nIn 1989, a researcher from Addis Ababa University spent three months with Wako recording his oral accounts. The resulting archive — over sixty hours of recordings — is now held at the university\'s Institute of Ethiopian Studies and remains one of the most comprehensive records of Bale Oromo customary law and history in existence. Wako insisted on one condition: everything must be recorded in Afaan Oromoo first, with translation secondary. "The meaning lives inside the language," he said. "When you take it out, something is always left behind."\n\nHe participated in Gadaa ceremonies into his seventies, walking long distances to be present even when his health was poor. He refused to allow the ceremonies to be abbreviated or modernised for convenience. He believed that partial preservation was a kind of forgetting dressed in the clothes of memory.\n\nWako Guutuu died peacefully in 2018 at the age of eighty-three. At the ceremony marking his death, his eldest son recited a genealogy stretching back seventeen generations — knowledge that Wako himself had passed to him. Those who heard it said the names sounded like water returning to its source.', 'story_om': ''}, 'fatuma-bedane': {'story': 'Fatuma Bedane came into the world in 1948 on the same mat on which she would later deliver more than three thousand children. Her mother was a midwife, and her grandmother before her. The knowledge moved between them not through books but through hands — the precise pressure needed to turn a breech, the herb that slowed dangerous bleeding, the words whispered to a frightened young mother to bring her breathing back to calm.\n\nFatuma grew up in Shashamane during a time when hospitals were hours away and largely inaccessible to poor Oromo families. The nearest clinic had no female staff, and many women refused to give birth there on cultural grounds. So Fatuma became the clinic — walking at all hours, in all weathers, across distances that would exhaust younger women.\n\nShe kept a careful record of every birth she attended. By the 1990s she had a leather-bound ledger containing the names, birth dates, and first cries of over two thousand children. She added notes about complications she had encountered and how she had managed them. These notes caught the attention of a visiting nurse from a regional health organisation, who worked with Fatuma over two years to have her knowledge translated into a training manual used across southern Oromiyaa.\n\nBut Fatuma was always more than a midwife. She maintained a herb garden that supplied medicines to her entire neighbourhood. She treated infections, set simple fractures, prepared medicines for fever and stomach illness. When a pharmaceutical shortage left her community without basic medicines in 2004, she quietly returned to methods that her grandmother had taught her and kept the neighbourhood healthy through the gap.\n\nShe was also an unflinching advocate. When a family tried to arrange the early marriage of a twelve-year-old girl, Fatuma walked to their home and sat in their courtyard until they agreed to wait. She told them: "I have brought too many of our daughters into the world to watch them be given away before they know their own name." The girl later became a nurse.\n\nFatuma Bedane died in 2022 at the age of seventy-four, at home, surrounded by the sounds of the town she had served her entire life. Her leather ledger is kept by her eldest daughter, who has continued the work.', 'story_en': 'Fatuma Bedane came into the world in 1948 on the same mat on which she would later deliver more than three thousand children. Her mother was a midwife, and her grandmother before her. The knowledge moved between them not through books but through hands — the precise pressure needed to turn a breech, the herb that slowed dangerous bleeding, the words whispered to a frightened young mother to bring her breathing back to calm.\n\nFatuma grew up in Shashamane during a time when hospitals were hours away and largely inaccessible to poor Oromo families. The nearest clinic had no female staff, and many women refused to give birth there on cultural grounds. So Fatuma became the clinic — walking at all hours, in all weathers, across distances that would exhaust younger women.\n\nShe kept a careful record of every birth she attended. By the 1990s she had a leather-bound ledger containing the names, birth dates, and first cries of over two thousand children. She added notes about complications she had encountered and how she had managed them. These notes caught the attention of a visiting nurse from a regional health organisation, who worked with Fatuma over two years to have her knowledge translated into a training manual used across southern Oromiyaa.\n\nBut Fatuma was always more than a midwife. She maintained a herb garden that supplied medicines to her entire neighbourhood. She treated infections, set simple fractures, prepared medicines for fever and stomach illness. When a pharmaceutical shortage left her community without basic medicines in 2004, she quietly returned to methods that her grandmother had taught her and kept the neighbourhood healthy through the gap.\n\nShe was also an unflinching advocate. When a family tried to arrange the early marriage of a twelve-year-old girl, Fatuma walked to their home and sat in their courtyard until they agreed to wait. She told them: "I have brought too many of our daughters into the world to watch them be given away before they know their own name." The girl later became a nurse.\n\nFatuma Bedane died in 2022 at the age of seventy-four, at home, surrounded by the sounds of the town she had served her entire life. Her leather ledger is kept by her eldest daughter, who has continued the work.', 'story_om': ''}, 'asnake-lemma': {'story': 'Asnake Lemma grew up watching his neighbours lose everything to a single failed harvest. Born in 1953 in the fertile but weather-dependent highlands near Robe, he understood from boyhood that the land could give and take with equal indifference. What he set out to change was not the land, but the loneliness with which farmers faced it.\n\nIn 1981, after years of informal organising among neighbouring families, Asnake established the Bale Farmers Cooperative — not as a government initiative, but as a community arrangement under which members pooled tools, shared water rights, and collectively negotiated with distant market traders who otherwise set exploitative prices. He typed the founding charter himself on a borrowed typewriter.\n\nHis greatest achievement was the seed bank he created in 1994. Alarmed that traditional seed varieties were disappearing as commercial hybrids entered the market, Asnake began collecting indigenous sorghum, teff, and barley varieties from elderly farmers who remembered cultivating them. He stored over sixty-three distinct varieties in sealed clay pots in a temperature-stable cellar, labelled in Afaan Oromoo with their traditional names and growing histories.\n\nDuring the 2002 drought that devastated much of Bale, Asnake\'s seed bank was the only source of locally adapted seed for four surrounding villages. Farmers who had planted commercial varieties lost everything. Farmers who drew from his store — using traditional varieties adapted to the soil over centuries — recovered within one growing season.\n\nAsnake Lemma never sought recognition. He refused to attend a ceremony held in his honour in 2014, sending his youngest daughter in his place. When asked why, he said he was too busy preparing the next season\'s soil. He died in 2021 at the age of sixty-eight. The seed bank he founded continues to operate, now holding over a hundred indigenous varieties. A hand-painted sign on its door reads: "He who preserves the seed preserves the people."', 'story_en': 'Asnake Lemma grew up watching his neighbours lose everything to a single failed harvest. Born in 1953 in the fertile but weather-dependent highlands near Robe, he understood from boyhood that the land could give and take with equal indifference. What he set out to change was not the land, but the loneliness with which farmers faced it.\n\nIn 1981, after years of informal organising among neighbouring families, Asnake established the Bale Farmers Cooperative — not as a government initiative, but as a community arrangement under which members pooled tools, shared water rights, and collectively negotiated with distant market traders who otherwise set exploitative prices. He typed the founding charter himself on a borrowed typewriter.\n\nHis greatest achievement was the seed bank he created in 1994. Alarmed that traditional seed varieties were disappearing as commercial hybrids entered the market, Asnake began collecting indigenous sorghum, teff, and barley varieties from elderly farmers who remembered cultivating them. He stored over sixty-three distinct varieties in sealed clay pots in a temperature-stable cellar, labelled in Afaan Oromoo with their traditional names and growing histories.\n\nDuring the 2002 drought that devastated much of Bale, Asnake\'s seed bank was the only source of locally adapted seed for four surrounding villages. Farmers who had planted commercial varieties lost everything. Farmers who drew from his store — using traditional varieties adapted to the soil over centuries — recovered within one growing season.\n\nAsnake Lemma never sought recognition. He refused to attend a ceremony held in his honour in 2014, sending his youngest daughter in his place. When asked why, he said he was too busy preparing the next season\'s soil. He died in 2021 at the age of sixty-eight. The seed bank he founded continues to operate, now holding over a hundred indigenous varieties. A hand-painted sign on its door reads: "He who preserves the seed preserves the people."', 'story_om': ''}, 'tolosa-qottu': {'story': 'Tolosa Qottu was born in 1941 in the highland town of Ginnir, Bale, at a time when the Oromo people navigated their lives under a feudal system that gave little weight to their customs and language. His father, a smallholder farmer, noticed the boy\'s unusual ability to listen — truly listen — to both sides of a dispute before speaking a single word. It was a gift that would define his life.\n\nAt twenty-two, Tolosa walked eleven kilometres each morning to attend a regional school that offered instruction in the evenings after government workers had finished for the day. He studied law on his own with borrowed textbooks, passing each examination with the quiet determination that later became his reputation. By 1968 he was serving as a community magistrate, one of the first Oromo men in Bale to hold such a role.\n\nHis courtroom was a room with no electricity and one ceiling fan that rarely worked. But people came from as far as four zones away to have Tolosa hear their cases. He was known for a method he called "sitting beneath the Odaa" — he would open court beneath the shade of whatever large tree stood near the courthouse, inviting elders and community members to witness proceedings. He believed justice must never be hidden.\n\nDuring the years of the Derg, when Oromo customs were suppressed and many community institutions dismantled, Tolosa maintained what he could in quiet ways. He recorded customary law principles in handwritten notebooks, preserving the principles of Gadaa governance so they would not disappear. He buried two of those notebooks under his courtyard when soldiers searched his house in 1979.\n\nHe retired in 2003 after thirty-five years of service, having presided over thousands of cases and never once, by the account of those who knew him, being shown to have accepted a bribe or ruled in favour of a wealthy party over a poor one simply because of their status. He spent his retirement years teaching young law students who came to his home on the weekends.\n\nTolosa Qottu died in 2019 at the age of seventy-eight. At his funeral, an elder from a distant district said simply: "He was the court and the law and the mercy, all in one man." His notebooks of customary law have since been donated to the Oromiyaa Cultural Heritage Institute.', 'story_en': 'Tolosa Qottu was born in 1941 in the highland town of Ginnir, Bale, at a time when the Oromo people navigated their lives under a feudal system that gave little weight to their customs and language. His father, a smallholder farmer, noticed the boy\'s unusual ability to listen — truly listen — to both sides of a dispute before speaking a single word. It was a gift that would define his life.\n\nAt twenty-two, Tolosa walked eleven kilometres each morning to attend a regional school that offered instruction in the evenings after government workers had finished for the day. He studied law on his own with borrowed textbooks, passing each examination with the quiet determination that later became his reputation. By 1968 he was serving as a community magistrate, one of the first Oromo men in Bale to hold such a role.\n\nHis courtroom was a room with no electricity and one ceiling fan that rarely worked. But people came from as far as four zones away to have Tolosa hear their cases. He was known for a method he called "sitting beneath the Odaa" — he would open court beneath the shade of whatever large tree stood near the courthouse, inviting elders and community members to witness proceedings. He believed justice must never be hidden.\n\nDuring the years of the Derg, when Oromo customs were suppressed and many community institutions dismantled, Tolosa maintained what he could in quiet ways. He recorded customary law principles in handwritten notebooks, preserving the principles of Gadaa governance so they would not disappear. He buried two of those notebooks under his courtyard when soldiers searched his house in 1979.\n\nHe retired in 2003 after thirty-five years of service, having presided over thousands of cases and never once, by the account of those who knew him, being shown to have accepted a bribe or ruled in favour of a wealthy party over a poor one simply because of their status. He spent his retirement years teaching young law students who came to his home on the weekends.\n\nTolosa Qottu died in 2019 at the age of seventy-eight. At his funeral, an elder from a distant district said simply: "He was the court and the law and the mercy, all in one man." His notebooks of customary law have since been donated to the Oromiyaa Cultural Heritage Institute.', 'story_om': ''}}


def restore_stories(apps, schema_editor):
    Legacy = apps.get_model('legacies', 'Legacy')
    for slug, fields in HERO_STORIES.items():
        Legacy.objects.filter(slug=slug).update(
            story=fields['story'],
            story_en=fields['story_en'],
            story_om=fields['story_om'],
        )


def noop(apps, schema_editor):
    pass


class Migration(migrations.Migration):

    dependencies = [
        ('legacies', '0009_fix_photo_paths'),
    ]

    operations = [
        migrations.RunPython(restore_stories, noop),
    ]
